Monthly pm2.5 in Bangkok : Comparing means

Inspired by prasertcbs
Raw data here

From this plot

Question : Does monthly seasonal variation in pm 2.5 exist ?

Descriptive Stat

Step 1 : Distribution is Normal or not ?

We can check this in 2 ways : 1) Inspect QQ plot , 2) Perform Shapiros test

1) QQ plot

ggqqplot(pm2_5.monthly , "pm2.5", facet.by = "month")

Data not in standard error range , It looks like non-normal distribution

2) Shapiros test

\(H_0\) : Normal distribution in sample

All non-normal distribution , comfirmed !!

Thus, We have to use non-parametric alternative to the one-way ANOVA test, Kruskal-Wallis Test.

Kruskal-Wallis Test

Data Novia

\[H_0 : \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3 = \ ...\ = \mu_{12}\] \[H_0 : \mu_1 \neq \mu_2 \neq \mu_3 \neq \ ...\ \neq \mu_{12}\]

P-value very close to 0 ?

Use Base R instead !

kruskal.test(pm2.5 ~ month, pm2_5.monthly)


    Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

data:  pm2.5 by month
Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 14988, df = 11, p-value < 2.2e-16

P-value is significant. Thus,there are at least one difference in mean pm2.5 between months.
But, how much of the differences ?

Kruskal effectsize calculation

pm2_5.monthly %>% rstatix::kruskal_effsize(pm2.5 ~ month)

Warning messages:
1: In readChar(file, size, TRUE) : truncating string with embedded nuls
2: In readChar(file, size, TRUE) : truncating string with embedded nuls

Meaning : 44% of variation in mean pm2.5 can be predicted by month. This effect size is large !!

Multiple pairwise-comparisons

From the output of the Kruskal-Wallis test, we know that there is a significant difference between groups, but we dont know which pairs of groups are different.

Dunns test

dunn_pm2_5.month <- pm2_5.monthly %>%

8: In readChar(file, size, TRUE) : truncating string with embedded nuls
        rstatix::dunn_test(pm2.5 ~ month, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")
dunn_pm2_5.month %>%
  mutate(mean_diff = if_else(p.adj > 0.001, "Non-Significant","Significant" )) %>%
  mutate(across(starts_with("g"),as_factor)) %>%
  select(".y.",starts_with("group"),p.adj,mean_diff) %>%
  arrange(desc(p.adj)) 
NA

Visualize significant Dunns test

Final Report

  • There was a statistically significant differences of pm2.5 mean value between months as assessed using the Kruskal-Wallis test (p < 0.001). Pairwise Dunns test between months showed that all the difference between months was significant (Dunns test, p < 0.001) except for 7 pairs of months as indicated by red dot in above graph.
